The exact value of
[
\lim_{r\to\infty}\frac{h(r)}{r^2}
]
is **not known** (this is an Erdős–Graham open problem). ([Erdős Problems][1])

What *is* known is that $h(r)$ grows quadratically in $r$, and the best current bounds pin the ratio down to an interval:

* Erdős–Graham proved $h(r)$ is (\Theta(r^2)), with bounds implying (in modern language)
  [
  \frac14 \ \le\ \liminf_{r\to\infty}\frac{h(r)}{r^2}
  \ \le\
  \limsup_{r\to\infty}\frac{h(r)}{r^2}
  \ \le\ \frac54.
  ]
  ([Erdős Problems][1])

* The **best bounds currently known** improve this to
  [
  \frac13 \ \le\ \liminf_{r\to\infty}\frac{h(r)}{r^2}
  \ \le\
  \limsup_{r\to\infty}\frac{h(r)}{r^2}
  \ \le\ \frac12,
  ]
  with the lower bound due to **Grekos** and the upper bound due to **Nash**. ([Erdős Problems][1])

So, **if the limit exists**, it must lie in $[1/3,1/2]$; and in any case the ratio has accumulation points only in that interval with current knowledge. ([Erdős Problems][1])

